[ Children chattering ]

74
00:06:56,484 --> 00:06:58,686
[ Church bell tolling ]

75
00:07:00,821 --> 00:07:02,656
[ Bell continues tolling ]

76
00:07:41,094 --> 00:07:44,264
[ Man ] 
 What a day, and what a way 
 to bring in the new year.

77
00:07:44,297 --> 00:07:46,767
This is the biggest 
 tournament of roses 
 parade yet.

78
00:07:48,235 --> 00:07:51,038
Each of the 102 floats 
 is a complex work...

79
00:07:51,071 --> 00:07:53,807
Of mechanical wizardry 
 and computer control.

80
00:07:53,841 --> 00:07:56,910
* [ Marching Band Continues ]

81
00:07:56,944 --> 00:08:02,182
Today, as millions of people 
 watch and tens of thousands 
 are here in pasadena,

82
00:08:02,215 --> 00:08:04,552
the tournament is 
 celebrating the theme 
 of vincent van gogh...

83
00:08:04,585 --> 00:08:06,787
And his great paintings 
 of flowers.

84
00:08:06,820 --> 00:08:09,790
Van gogh painted 
 all types of flowers, 
 but his sunflowers, perhaps,

85
00:08:09,823 --> 00:08:12,826
are among the most popular 
 in the world.

86
00:08:12,860 --> 00:08:16,864
Although he died penniless, 
 today his paintings are worth 
 hundreds millions of dollars,

87
00:08:16,897 --> 00:08:19,232
and he's honored 
 as an artistic genius.

88
00:08:19,266 --> 00:08:24,638
Like so many great artists, 
 in his own time van gogh 
 was completely rejected.

89
00:08:24,672 --> 00:08:27,240
People simply didn't 
 understand his paintings.

90
00:08:30,944 --> 00:08:35,015
- [ Man shouting ] 
 - [ Woman ] 
 Oh, my god. [ Screams ]

91
00:08:35,048 --> 00:08:37,050
[ Announcer ] 
 Just a moment.

92
00:08:37,084 --> 00:08:40,153
There's some sort of emergency 
 down on the parade route.

93
00:08:40,187 --> 00:08:43,957
Oh, the parade has stopped. 
 Apparently, someone has been 
 struck by one of the floats.

94
00:08:43,991 --> 00:08:48,061
It's a man. 
 We don't know the extent 
 of his injuries.

95
00:08:48,095 --> 00:08:50,130
We're being told 
 he was dressed as--

96
00:08:50,163 --> 00:08:53,033
[ Chuckles ] 
 As vincent van gogh.

97
00:08:53,066 --> 00:08:56,069
There's some confusion 
 as to whether or not he was 
 part of that float.

98
00:08:56,103 --> 00:08:58,706
We'll keep you up to date 
 on that story as it develops.

99
00:09:00,674 --> 00:09:05,979
Hello!
 Have you had an accident
 and it wasn't your fault?

100
00:09:06,013 --> 00:09:08,348
Maybe you've been getting
 hit from all sides...

101
00:09:08,381 --> 00:09:11,151
And think there's nowhere
 to turn to for help.

102
00:09:11,184 --> 00:09:13,821
Well, relief is here.

103
00:09:13,854 --> 00:09:16,990
Call me, gabe burton,
 attorney at law,

104
00:09:17,024 --> 00:09:20,127
because I want to give you
 what's coming to you,

105
00:09:20,160 --> 00:09:23,096
and I'll give them back
 what's coming to them.

106
00:09:23,130 --> 00:09:25,766
So, call ME:

107
00:09:30,704 --> 00:09:33,273
Hey, honey.
 Honey, honey, honey!

108
00:09:33,306 --> 00:09:37,277
My ad's on tv!
 Ah! This is gonna
 change everything!

109
00:09:37,310 --> 00:09:39,880
I'm back in business again!

110
00:09:41,982 --> 00:09:44,317
Honey, I'm trying to video
 our new year's day party,

111
00:09:44,351 --> 00:09:47,721
and you're blocking
the view!

112
00:09:47,755 --> 00:09:51,959
[ Wife ] oh, I'm blocking 
 the view? Get down from there 
 before you break your leg!

113
00:09:51,992 --> 00:09:55,763
Come on, honey. 
 Don't you think that 
 I've learned my lesson?

114
00:09:55,796 --> 00:09:59,032
- move out of the way.
 - move out of the way?
 Get off the ladder!

115
00:09:59,066 --> 00:10:02,102
Get off the ladder, gabe.
 Get off the ladder!
 No, no, no, no--

116
00:10:02,135 --> 00:10:05,038
- don't shake the ladder! 
 - oh, gabe, not again!

117
00:10:05,072 --> 00:10:07,074
Call 9-1-1.

118
00:10:08,241 --> 00:10:10,377
Hey, buddy,
I've been thinking.

119
00:10:10,410 --> 00:10:13,647
Maybe you should sue
 those rose parade people.

120
00:10:13,681 --> 00:10:17,718
I-i-i'm used to handling
 personal injury cases.
 I could be your attorney.

121
00:10:17,751 --> 00:10:19,853
The brakes didn't work
on that float that hit you,

122
00:10:19,887 --> 00:10:22,790
and so you became
 the only person
 in history...

123
00:10:22,823 --> 00:10:26,226
To be run over
 at the rose parade
 on live national television.

124
00:10:26,259 --> 00:10:29,730
You suffered physical injury
 and emotional distress.

125
00:10:29,763 --> 00:10:31,999
[ Chuckles ]
 Oh, ho, ho, boy!

126
00:10:32,032 --> 00:10:35,936
That's a two-million-dollar
out-of-court settlement
if I ever heard one!

127
00:10:35,969 --> 00:10:38,405
So, what do you think,
 buddy?

128
00:10:38,438 --> 00:10:40,340
What are you
 looking at?

129
00:10:40,373 --> 00:10:43,877
This painting!
 It's starry night!

130
00:10:43,911 --> 00:10:48,081
- but there's no paint.
 - well, of course not.
 That's a color print.

131
00:10:48,115 --> 00:10:52,385
- color engraving?
 - no, no. You know, 
 a-a-a-- a print!

132
00:10:52,419 --> 00:10:56,089
They take these famous
 pictures and reproduce
 zillions of 'em.

133
00:10:56,123 --> 00:10:58,892
But the entire effect
 has been destroyed.

134
00:10:58,926 --> 00:11:01,862
I intended this to have
 thick colors and textures.

135
00:11:01,895 --> 00:11:03,864
What do you mean,
 yo intended?

136
00:11:03,897 --> 00:11:06,133
Vincent van gogh
 painted starry night.

137
00:11:06,166 --> 00:11:10,003
Yes. Of course.

138
00:11:10,037 --> 00:11:13,306
Let me see how you're coming
 with my, uh, face.

139
00:11:13,340 --> 00:11:15,976
Oh, that's not bad.

140
00:11:16,009 --> 00:11:18,879
Not bad! Y-y-you got
 some great talent there.

141
00:11:18,912 --> 00:11:20,881
You think?
 How much you want
 for this?

142
00:11:20,914 --> 00:11:23,450
[ Chuckles ]
 I don't know.
 A hundred bucks?

143
00:11:23,483 --> 00:11:26,754
- a hundred bucks?
- you drive a hard bargain.

144
00:11:26,787 --> 00:11:28,789
Two hundred bucks,
 take it or leave it.

145
00:11:28,822 --> 00:11:30,891
I'll take it.
 Thank you.

146
00:11:30,924 --> 00:11:35,095
Two hundred bucks.
 You must have told me
 before, but I, uh--

147
00:11:35,128 --> 00:11:38,031
what is your name?
 Gabe.
 Gabe burton.

148
00:11:38,065 --> 00:11:41,168
Burton.
 I am vincent.
 And yours?

149
00:11:41,201 --> 00:11:44,805
Nice to meet you,
 vincent.
 Nice to meet you, gabe.

150
00:11:44,838 --> 00:11:48,108
How much is this worth
 in guilders?

151
00:11:48,141 --> 00:11:50,844
Guilders.
 I don't know.
 [ Chuckles ]

152
00:11:50,878 --> 00:11:54,481
- francs?
 - about 1,100 francs,
 give or take.

153
00:11:54,514 --> 00:11:59,286
No! 1,100?
You are too generous, gabe.

154
00:11:59,319 --> 00:12:01,989
I should paint your portrait
 for this much money.

155
00:12:02,022 --> 00:12:04,792
- in oils?
 - in oils, yes.

156
00:12:04,825 --> 00:12:07,795
You'd have to pose
 for me, of course.
 All right!

157
00:12:08,528 --> 00:12:11,064
You're not bad, vincent.

158
00:12:11,098 --> 00:12:14,868
Give me a buzz
 when we get out of here,
 and we'll touch base.

159
00:12:14,902 --> 00:12:17,971
I will give you buzz...

160
00:12:18,005 --> 00:12:21,541
And will touch the base.

161
00:12:21,574 --> 00:12:25,112
"Gabe burton,
 attorney at law."

162
00:12:25,145 --> 00:12:32,019
To think I only got 400 francs
 when I sold my first painting
 to anna boch.

163
00:12:32,052 --> 00:12:37,257
Hundreds of beautiful 
 paintings I made in a 
 five-year period,

164
00:12:37,290 --> 00:12:40,460
and nobody was interested
 in one of them, not one.

165
00:12:40,493 --> 00:12:45,032
And now, look.
 I seem to be famous and
 hanging on people's walls.

166
00:12:45,065 --> 00:12:48,001
And they make prints
 of my work!

167
00:12:48,035 --> 00:12:51,138
Hey, wait a minute there.
 Where are you going?

168
00:12:51,171 --> 00:12:54,875
You need to sign
 this book out.
 Oh, I beg your pardon.

169
00:12:54,908 --> 00:13:00,380
- right there.
 - right there.
 And there you go.

170
00:13:00,413 --> 00:13:04,184
Thank you.
 Vincent van gogh?
 Thank you.

171
00:13:04,217 --> 00:13:06,486
- that's right.
 - I am not in the mood
 for jokes.

172
00:13:06,519 --> 00:13:09,222
Oh, it's no joke.
 Now, may I go?

173
00:13:09,256 --> 00:13:12,059
Please,
 sign your real name!

174
00:13:12,092 --> 00:13:15,896
Gabe, let me show you
 something I found in
 this good book.

175
00:13:15,929 --> 00:13:19,032
Here. Here there's
 a picture of me.

176
00:13:19,066 --> 00:13:21,368
An excellent likeness, 
 don't you think?

177
00:13:21,401 --> 00:13:25,839
Spittin' image.
Except that's a picture
of vincent van gogh.

178
00:13:25,873 --> 00:13:28,208
Yes, it is.
 That's what I'm saying.

179
00:13:28,241 --> 00:13:30,343
I am vincent van gogh.

180
00:13:30,377 --> 00:13:35,949
- oh, boy.
 - my dear friend paul gauguin
 painted this of me.

181
00:13:35,983 --> 00:13:39,186
- nurse!
 - [ Telephone ringing ]

182
00:13:39,219 --> 00:13:42,422
Well, well.

183
00:13:42,455 --> 00:13:46,359
I hear you two youngsters
 were up early this morning
 terrorizing the nursing staff.

184
00:13:46,393 --> 00:13:50,197
Glad you're feelin' better.
Got to look at your, uh,
bandage here first.

185
00:13:50,230 --> 00:13:53,433
I don't see why I need it.
 Well, you have
 a very serious injury.

186
00:13:53,466 --> 00:13:56,870
How serious?
 The lobe of your left ear
 was completely severed.

187
00:13:56,904 --> 00:13:58,939
No.
 Yes, it was.

188
00:13:58,972 --> 00:14:01,141
No, it wasn't.
 No, it wasn't.
 Yes, it was.

189
00:14:01,174 --> 00:14:03,877
I cut if off myself
 a long time ago.

190
00:14:28,101 --> 00:14:31,538
[ Snoring ]

191
00:14:34,107 --> 00:14:37,177
[ Sighing ]

192
00:14:40,013 --> 00:14:41,581
[ Sneezes ]

193
00:15:26,626 --> 00:15:29,129
[ Wind gusting ]

194
00:15:29,162 --> 00:15:30,964
[ Traffic passing, 
 horn blowing ]

195
00:15:45,345 --> 00:15:47,180
[ Woman ] 
 Let's just forget about it, 
 all right?

196
00:15:47,214 --> 00:15:50,250
Oh, come on, kathy.
Will you grow up?
 [ Sighs ]

197
00:15:50,283 --> 00:15:53,286
Now, why can't
 you just get over
 your crazy obsession?

198
00:15:53,320 --> 00:15:55,322
Obsession?
 Is that what
 you think this is?

199
00:15:55,355 --> 00:15:58,125
Yeah. And have
 a real life here
 with me.

200
00:15:58,158 --> 00:16:00,027
I have a life, chuck.

201
00:16:00,060 --> 00:16:02,262
Oh, you wanna waste your
 life living for your art.

202
00:16:02,295 --> 00:16:04,231
You can be so insensitive!

203
00:16:04,264 --> 00:16:07,500
That's the reason
 we're breaking up, chuck.
 No, I am not insensitive.

204
00:16:07,534 --> 00:16:10,303
I am just practical
 in my approach to life.

205
00:16:10,337 --> 00:16:13,206
I wanna make a wish.

206
00:16:13,240 --> 00:16:16,276
[ Thinking ]
I want to be appreciated
as an artist and a woman...

207
00:16:16,309 --> 00:16:18,745
And I want to know love.

208
00:16:23,550 --> 00:16:25,518
What was your wish?

209
00:16:28,688 --> 00:16:32,125
- what was your wish?
 - you wouldn't understand.

210
00:17:12,765 --> 00:17:18,071
[ Laughing ] so, chuck 
 wants me to go to the park 
 city film festival with him.

211
00:17:18,105 --> 00:17:20,307
God, I thought
 you two broke up.
 Oh, we did.

212
00:17:20,340 --> 00:17:23,676
But, you know, we're still 
 just friends. You know, 
 I can see it NOW:

213
00:17:23,710 --> 00:17:26,646
He'll say okay,
 we show up at the hotel,
 and suddenly...

214
00:17:26,679 --> 00:17:29,349
There's one room left,
 with a double bed.
 [ Laughs ] yup.

215
00:17:29,382 --> 00:17:31,851
So, sha--
 ow, my foot!
 Oh, stop!

216
00:17:31,884 --> 00:17:35,655
- somebody help. My foot!
 - give it back. Ow, stop!

217
00:17:35,688 --> 00:17:39,392
[ All clamoring,
 robber growling ]

218
00:17:51,538 --> 00:17:55,575
Are you all right?
 Yeah, I'm fine. I'll probably
 have some bruises to remind me

219
00:17:55,608 --> 00:17:59,246
are you all right?
 Yes, yes.

220
00:17:59,279 --> 00:18:04,451
That was a mean and
 destructive human soul.
 Thank you.

221
00:18:04,484 --> 00:18:07,787
You're welcome.
 Hardly fit for
 human society.

222
00:18:07,820 --> 00:18:12,292
[ Panting ]
 May I escort you home?
 Oh, no, thanks.

223
00:18:12,325 --> 00:18:15,428
We just live right over there.
 The building with
 the billboard.

224
00:18:15,462 --> 00:18:17,730
But we're not going home 
 right now. 
 [ Vincent ] right there?

225
00:18:17,764 --> 00:18:21,334
Yes. You know, I don't
 have much money, but please,
 let me give you a reward.

226
00:18:21,368 --> 00:18:23,336
No, no.
 I won't hear of it.

227
00:18:23,370 --> 00:18:25,805
It's enough to know
 that I've helped you.

228
00:18:25,838 --> 00:18:29,776
That's reward enough for me.
 Well, thank you.

229
00:18:29,809 --> 00:18:32,712
Thank you very much.

230
00:18:32,745 --> 00:18:35,648
Are you okay?
 Thanks.
 I am. Thanks.

231
00:18:35,682 --> 00:18:39,419
God, I can't believe it.
 Did you see that guy?
 He had tattoos all the way--

232
00:18:39,452 --> 00:18:41,554
he did. 
 Oh, god.

233
00:19:22,629 --> 00:19:25,632
I would still like 
 to help you sue 
 the rose parade.

234
00:19:25,665 --> 00:19:28,535
In fact, I'll even
 waive my retainer,

235
00:19:28,568 --> 00:19:30,637
since you're
 so flat broke.

236
00:19:30,670 --> 00:19:34,307
Unless, of course,
you're still cashing in
from some of these, uh,

237
00:19:34,341 --> 00:19:36,743
van gogh paintings,
huh?

238
00:19:36,776 --> 00:19:41,414
Boy, you know,
 it's too bad that, uh--

239
00:19:41,448 --> 00:19:45,385
that some of this money 
 isn't going into your pocket.

240
00:19:45,418 --> 00:19:47,954
What are my paintings
 selling for these days, gabe?

241
00:19:47,987 --> 00:19:53,693
Uh, van gogh's sunflowers 
 sold to a japanese insurance
 company for 33.

242
00:19:53,726 --> 00:19:55,928
Thirty-three dollars?
 Not bad.

243
00:19:55,962 --> 00:19:58,231
Thirty-three
 millio dollars.

244
00:20:00,733 --> 00:20:03,236
- that's impossible!
 - oh, you wanna bet?

245
00:20:03,270 --> 00:20:05,672
And that was just
 a low-ball price.

246
00:20:05,705 --> 00:20:08,375
Irises went to alan bond
 of australia...

247
00:20:08,408 --> 00:20:10,943
In 1987, for 54!

248
00:20:10,977 --> 00:20:15,282
- fifty-four... Million?
 - well, of course, million.

249
00:20:15,315 --> 00:20:19,552
And, uh,
 portrait of uh,
 doctor "gachette"--

250
00:20:19,586 --> 00:20:21,788
"gash-ay."
 Doctor gachet.

251
00:20:21,821 --> 00:20:25,358
Portrait of Dr. "Gash-ay"
 Sold for 78...

252
00:20:25,392 --> 00:20:27,694
To some japanese collector.

253
00:20:27,727 --> 00:20:32,765
Oh, and look at THIS: 
 Alex manners just paid 
 65 million bucks...

254
00:20:32,799 --> 00:20:35,402
For self-portrait 
 at "auvairs."

255
00:20:35,435 --> 00:20:38,037
"Au-vair."
 Self-portrait at auvers.

256
00:20:38,070 --> 00:20:40,440
I don't understand.

257
00:20:40,473 --> 00:20:44,977
If my paintings 
 are worth so much, 
 why am I so broke?

258
00:20:45,011 --> 00:20:49,382
- it's not fair.
 - ahh! Who said
 life was fair?

259
00:20:49,416 --> 00:20:52,685
That's so much
 money I could do
 good things with, gabe.

260
00:20:52,719 --> 00:20:55,021
There's many worthy causes
 out there.

261
00:20:55,054 --> 00:20:57,390
Yeah, well,
 keep dreaming, kid.

262
00:20:57,424 --> 00:21:00,293
I'm sure the, uh,
"check is in the mail."

263
00:21:00,327 --> 00:21:04,597
Where does that collector live
 That one that just bought
 my self-portrait?

264
00:21:04,631 --> 00:21:06,699
Crescent drive,
 in beverly hills.

265
00:21:06,733 --> 00:21:08,835
[ Chattering, 
 women laughing ]

266
00:21:27,854 --> 00:21:29,922
[ Electronic alarm 
 chirping ]

267
00:21:31,123 --> 00:21:34,394
Alex. Alex!

268
00:21:34,427 --> 00:21:37,564
Don't shoot!
 You might put a hole
 in the painting.

269
00:22:05,392 --> 00:22:07,560
That's not bad.

270
00:22:07,594 --> 00:22:09,996
I mean,
 it's fantastic, actually.

271
00:22:10,029 --> 00:22:14,000
- thank you for saying so.
- I really like your style.

272
00:22:14,033 --> 00:22:16,669
You seem to really know
 how to let yourself go.

273
00:22:16,703 --> 00:22:19,439
How are you doing
after that terrible attack?

274
00:22:19,472 --> 00:22:22,008
I'm fine. Thanks.
 I'm sorry.

275
00:22:22,041 --> 00:22:26,413
- I forgot to ask your name.
 - kathy. And you're--

276
00:22:26,446 --> 00:22:28,881
I'm vincent.
 Vincent. Hi.

277
00:22:28,915 --> 00:22:30,950
Well, you're quite
 an artist, vincent.

278
00:22:30,983 --> 00:22:33,119
Thanks again for saying so.

279
00:22:33,152 --> 00:22:37,424
Uh, do you think that
 we could be friends?

280
00:22:37,457 --> 00:22:40,126
What do you mean,
 "friends"?

281
00:22:40,159 --> 00:22:43,062
Friends that talk to each
 other and say what they think.

282
00:22:43,095 --> 00:22:45,665
[ Sighs ]
 Think about what?

283
00:22:45,698 --> 00:22:50,403
About EVERYTHING:
 Life, creation,

284
00:22:50,437 --> 00:22:52,505
destiny, fate, wisdom-- 
 [ Chuckling ]

285
00:22:52,539 --> 00:22:57,644
- that's a start, isn't it?
 - [ Sighs ]
 Are you always so serious?

286
00:22:57,677 --> 00:23:00,613
- it's one of my faults.
 - hmm.

287
00:23:00,647 --> 00:23:03,683
Wh-- yes.
Yes, we can be friends.

288
00:23:05,084 --> 00:23:07,153
So, uh--
 did you move
 into the building?

289
00:23:07,186 --> 00:23:09,422
Uh, I live up on the roof.

290
00:23:09,456 --> 00:23:12,058
- how can you live
 on the roof?
 - it's not that bad,

291
00:23:12,091 --> 00:23:14,060
and it has a great view.

292
00:23:14,093 --> 00:23:18,898
- well, see you.
 - see you.

293
00:23:25,137 --> 00:23:29,075
How do you do, Mr. Manners?
 At the moment,
 not too well, thank you.

294
00:23:29,108 --> 00:23:32,579
This is where my van gogh
 was stolen from.

295
00:23:32,612 --> 00:23:35,214
Well, I'm
 detective brook murphy,
 art theft detail.

296
00:23:35,247 --> 00:23:37,016
I was up all night
 with the police,
 dusting for fingerprints.

297
00:23:37,049 --> 00:23:39,085
Thank you
 for following up
 so quickly.

298
00:23:39,118 --> 00:23:43,022
It's my job.
 What are my chances for
 getting it back?

299
00:23:43,055 --> 00:23:46,859
- slim to none?
 - I don't have a crystal ball,
 Mr. Manners.

300
00:23:46,893 --> 00:23:52,031
- you must know the odds.
 - art crimes accounted for two
 billion in losses last year,

301
00:23:52,064 --> 00:23:54,701
only a fraction of which
 was recovered.

302
00:23:54,734 --> 00:23:56,936
A fraction?
A fraction.

303
00:23:56,969 --> 00:23:59,138
Two billion 
 in losses?

304
00:23:59,171 --> 00:24:02,675
Two billion.
 Right behind
 drug trafficking.

305
00:24:02,709 --> 00:24:06,746
I don't suppose you've ever
 gone after a van gogh before,
 have you?

306
00:24:06,779 --> 00:24:10,082
Is that what you suppose, 
 Mr. Manners?

307
00:24:10,116 --> 00:24:13,085
I was the one
 who nailed losey--

308
00:24:13,119 --> 00:24:17,990
the con man
 who stole the renoir from
 the LA. County museum of art.

309
00:24:18,024 --> 00:24:21,060
- you're the one
 who arrested losey?
 - yes.

310
00:24:21,093 --> 00:24:24,497
I have spent ten years
 in this business, Mr. Manners.

311
00:24:24,531 --> 00:24:27,967
I have had over 350 cases,
 ranging from...

312
00:24:28,000 --> 00:24:31,804
Stolen greek statuary
 to solid gold
 hara-kiri knives...

313
00:24:31,838 --> 00:24:34,674
With sculpted handles
 by yoko ono.

314
00:24:35,842 --> 00:24:38,244
- mind if I look around?
 - be my guest.

315
00:24:42,148 --> 00:24:45,618
- times have changed,
 aunt gladys.
 - yes, they have. [ Sighs ]

316
00:24:46,886 --> 00:24:48,921
People are more
 independent these days.

317
00:24:48,955 --> 00:24:51,123
They have to be
 in order to survive.

318
00:24:51,157 --> 00:24:52,892
I don't understand
 you '90s women.

319
00:24:52,925 --> 00:24:57,764
Why is it so wrong 
 to fall in love and have 
 a normal, happy marriage?

320
00:24:57,797 --> 00:24:59,866
[ Sighs deeply ]

321
00:24:59,899 --> 00:25:03,035
Don't get me wrong.
 I would love to meet
 the right man.

322
00:25:03,069 --> 00:25:07,173
If that happens,
 that would be just
 fine with me.

323
00:25:08,340 --> 00:25:10,877
It'll happen
 if you let it happen.

324
00:25:10,910 --> 00:25:14,013
But it is not at the top
 of my agenda right now.

325
00:25:14,046 --> 00:25:17,216
Being established
 as an artist is.

326
00:25:17,249 --> 00:25:20,553
Why is it so many people
 are worried about
 their agenda these days,

327
00:25:20,587 --> 00:25:22,822
instead of having
 a happy life?

328
00:25:22,855 --> 00:25:24,824
[ Man on tv ] 
 ...With what's known 
 as an art terrorist,

329
00:25:24,857 --> 00:25:27,093
possibly even
 a renegade KG.B. Agent...

330
00:25:27,126 --> 00:25:30,830
Who's trying
 to undermine the economy
 of the western world.

331
00:25:30,863 --> 00:25:32,932
[ Male host ]
 Once again, for those viewers
 just joining us,

332
00:25:32,965 --> 00:25:35,635
detective brook murphy
 is on the prowl.

333
00:25:35,668 --> 00:25:39,906
Her number one target,
 the thief who stole van gogh's
 self-portrait at auvers.

334
00:25:39,939 --> 00:25:42,842
Isn't it true
that most art thieves
turn out to be con men?

335
00:25:42,875 --> 00:25:44,877
[ Murphy ]
 Well, that's just
 a stereotype.

336
00:25:44,911 --> 00:25:49,115
Your suave con man
 who has a french accent,
 drives a rolls-royce...

337
00:25:49,148 --> 00:25:51,584
And lives in
 a classy penthouse?

338
00:25:51,618 --> 00:25:54,020
- and it's not true.
 - sometimes.

339
00:25:54,053 --> 00:25:56,889
More often than not,
 it's your frustrated artist,

340
00:25:56,923 --> 00:26:00,159
your talented wanna-be 
 who couldn't quite make 
 a name for himself.

341
00:26:00,192 --> 00:26:03,596
So, instead of creating art,
 he steals it instead.

342
00:26:03,630 --> 00:26:05,665
[ Women chattering ]

343
00:26:10,703 --> 00:26:13,372
Huh! He's up there
 every day now.

344
00:26:13,405 --> 00:26:15,975
[ Other woman ] 
 You told him you live here, 
 and now he's stalking you.

345
00:26:16,008 --> 00:26:19,746
Wanna bet?
 Then you're naive.
 He is not.

346
00:26:19,779 --> 00:26:22,782
Wonder what he's painting.

347
00:26:25,017 --> 00:26:27,720
The hat makes the man.

348
00:26:27,754 --> 00:26:29,889
[ Siren wailing ]

349
00:26:33,225 --> 00:26:35,695
* [ Blues ]

350
00:26:40,166 --> 00:26:43,770
[ No audible dialogue ]

351
00:27:33,252 --> 00:27:38,090
Yeah, we found
 the van gogh this morning
 in the guardhouse.

352
00:27:38,124 --> 00:27:40,693
- guardhouse?
 - yes.

353
00:27:40,727 --> 00:27:44,931
In a plain box, wrapped up
 in brown wrapping paper.

354
00:27:44,964 --> 00:27:47,867
That's the most bizarre thing
 I've heard since...

355
00:27:47,900 --> 00:27:52,038
That 61-year-old truck driver
 stole a goya from the
 national gallery in london...

356
00:27:52,071 --> 00:27:54,974
And then got scared and left
 it in brown wrapping paper
 at the railroad station.

357
00:27:55,007 --> 00:27:59,912
There's something even
 stranger about this case.

358
00:28:02,882 --> 00:28:06,185
Oh, my god!

359
00:28:06,218 --> 00:28:10,089
It's one of the worst cases 
 of vandalism I've ever seen.

360
00:28:10,122 --> 00:28:14,693
It's a tragedy!
 This is the note
 the thief left.

361
00:28:25,004 --> 00:28:28,808
"Dear sirs,
 I never sold
 this self-portrait...

362
00:28:28,841 --> 00:28:33,379
"During my natural lifetime,
 therefore, as the artist,
 it belongs to me.

363
00:28:33,412 --> 00:28:36,382
"I've corrected 
 a serious flaw.

364
00:28:36,415 --> 00:28:39,786
"It needed a yellow hat 
 to make it cheerful.

365
00:28:39,819 --> 00:28:43,890
"I don't approve of my art
 being hoarded by
 private collectors.

366
00:28:43,923 --> 00:28:48,127
"I painted not just
 for the rich but for
 everyone who loves beauty.

367
00:28:48,160 --> 00:28:51,230
"Therefore I am proud
 to donate this work
 to your museum.

368
00:28:51,263 --> 00:28:54,166
- sincerely, vincent 
 van gogh." 
 - sheer lunacy.

369
00:28:56,368 --> 00:28:58,470
Maybe not.

370
00:28:58,504 --> 00:29:01,273
[ Scoffs ]
 How could it be
 anything else? Tell me.

371
00:29:01,307 --> 00:29:03,475
Might be
 a political statement.

372
00:29:03,509 --> 00:29:05,978
I fail to see
 the politics in it,
 frankly.

373
00:29:06,012 --> 00:29:08,781
There are organized groups
 in the third world.

374
00:29:08,815 --> 00:29:11,083
We call them 
 "art terrorists."

375
00:29:11,117 --> 00:29:15,087
They're determined to
 undermine the stability of the
 international art market.

376
00:29:15,121 --> 00:29:18,290
They thrive on creating
 economic chaos.

377
00:29:19,558 --> 00:29:22,829
I think maybe
 he's one of them.

378
00:29:22,862 --> 00:29:24,530
[ Knocking on door ]

379
00:29:24,563 --> 00:29:26,899
[ Kathy ] 
 Who is it?

380
00:29:26,933 --> 00:29:29,902
[ Knocking continues ]

381
00:29:29,936 --> 00:29:32,872
Yes?
 [ Vincent ] 
 It's me.

382
00:29:32,905 --> 00:29:36,242
You said 
 we could be friends. 
 Remember?

383
00:29:39,846 --> 00:29:43,515
Hello. Could we have
 that talk now?

384
00:29:43,549 --> 00:29:49,822
Are you busy?
 Oh! Uh, no.
 I-i-it's okay. Come in.

385
00:29:51,590 --> 00:29:54,126
What's that?
 Wine?

386
00:29:54,160 --> 00:29:57,163
Uh, no.
 It's the wormwood.

387
00:29:57,196 --> 00:29:59,932
What?
 Absinthe.

388
00:29:59,966 --> 00:30:03,535
Oh. Doesn't that taste
 sort of medicinal?

389
00:30:03,569 --> 00:30:07,173
[ Gags ]
 It's good medicine
 for the soul.

390
00:30:07,206 --> 00:30:10,342
Try some?
 Oh! Uh, no.

391
00:30:10,376 --> 00:30:13,179
Thank you, though.
 Please.

392
00:30:18,951 --> 00:30:23,155
I'm very embarrassed
 to tell you this, but I've
 forgotten your name,

393
00:30:23,189 --> 00:30:26,492
which is just so stupid,
 because you practically
 saved my life the other day.

394
00:30:26,525 --> 00:30:30,429
That's all right.
 I'm vincent.
 Vincent! Right!

395
00:30:30,462 --> 00:30:33,132
Kathy.
 Kathy.

396
00:30:33,165 --> 00:30:35,434
[ Chuckles ]
 Thank you again.

397
00:30:35,467 --> 00:30:37,469
Please. Please.

398
00:30:37,503 --> 00:30:40,206
Thank you.

399
00:30:40,239 --> 00:30:41,941
[ Sighs ]

400
00:30:44,110 --> 00:30:46,012
It's nice to have
 somebody to talk to.

401
00:30:49,648 --> 00:30:52,084
I've been lonely before.

402
00:30:52,118 --> 00:30:55,287
I used to have many friends 
 I could talk to.

403
00:30:55,321 --> 00:30:58,424
Wonderful friends.

404
00:30:58,457 --> 00:31:00,993
But they're all
 dead and gone.

405
00:31:01,027 --> 00:31:04,496
Tell me about you.
 You live here all alone?

406
00:31:04,530 --> 00:31:08,200
Uh, well, yes.
 Actually, my parents
 died a few years ago,

407
00:31:08,234 --> 00:31:12,238
and I've been here
on my own ever since
I started taking art class.

408
00:31:12,271 --> 00:31:15,174
So, you're
 an art student, then?
 Yes.

409
00:31:15,207 --> 00:31:19,178
Uh, but to tell you the truth,
 I don't know how much longer
 I'll be able to keep going.

410
00:31:19,211 --> 00:31:22,481
My paintings 
 aren't selling,

411
00:31:22,514 --> 00:31:25,684
and I really thought
they would have by now.

412
00:31:25,717 --> 00:31:28,955
But I guess that's
 the case with my other
 friends at school.

413
00:31:28,988 --> 00:31:31,190
I'd like to meet
 your other friends.

414
00:31:31,223 --> 00:31:36,195
Well, okay. Maybe
 you could come to, uh,
 class, you know, sometime.

415
00:31:36,228 --> 00:31:38,664
I'd love to do that.

416
00:31:54,180 --> 00:31:56,315
The thighs are too small.

417
00:31:56,348 --> 00:31:59,185
What?
 The thighs.

418
00:31:59,218 --> 00:32:02,654
They surround
 the female nectar.
 They need more flesh.

419
00:32:02,688 --> 00:32:05,657
And why don't you show 
 the fullness of her breasts?

420
00:32:05,691 --> 00:32:08,995
Because. This is how
 I see her, vincent.

421
00:32:09,028 --> 00:32:11,097
But you hide her flaws.

422
00:32:11,130 --> 00:32:13,165
You should make 
 every line count.

423
00:32:13,199 --> 00:32:16,668
- I don't want
 to make her look ugly.
 - the truth is never ugly.

424
00:32:16,702 --> 00:32:20,539
God made the truth.
 What's ugly are lies.

425
00:32:20,572 --> 00:32:22,474
Lies were invented
 by man.

426
00:32:22,508 --> 00:32:24,310
[ Biting apple ]

427
00:32:27,379 --> 00:32:29,648
Prepare yourself
 for a shock.

428
00:32:32,218 --> 00:32:36,622
- oh, my god!
 - sorry to be
 the bearer of bad news.

429
00:32:39,125 --> 00:32:44,396
What kind of a sick mind
 would do something like this?
 This is unspeakable!

430
00:32:44,430 --> 00:32:49,601
We see it all the time, 
 Mr. Manners. 
 Movies sensationalize it.

431
00:32:49,635 --> 00:32:52,638
Jack nicholson as the joker
in batm defaces art,

432
00:32:52,671 --> 00:32:56,542
spraying graffiti
 all over masterpieces
 in a museum;

433
00:32:56,575 --> 00:33:02,414
the maniac who threw paint 
 at th mona lisa in 1957.

434
00:33:02,448 --> 00:33:05,251
We see it all the time,
Mr. Manners.

435
00:33:05,284 --> 00:33:08,220
Excuse me, Detective murphy. 
 You have an urgent phone call.

436
00:33:10,556 --> 00:33:13,259
Excuse me.

437
00:33:13,292 --> 00:33:15,561
[ Perplexed sighing ]

438
00:33:15,594 --> 00:33:18,330
Hello.
 This is doctor moreau.

439
00:33:18,364 --> 00:33:21,700
I've made a very
 startling discovery.

440
00:33:21,733 --> 00:33:24,170
The thief's note
 that I have a copy of,

441
00:33:24,203 --> 00:33:28,474
I compared that with
the handwriting of van gogh
to his brother theo.

442
00:33:28,507 --> 00:33:31,543
Now, the note was forged
 to look exactly...

443
00:33:31,577 --> 00:33:34,080
Like the handwriting
 of van gogh.

444
00:33:34,113 --> 00:33:38,317
I mean, I have not seen
 a forgery this good...

445
00:33:38,350 --> 00:33:40,652
Since the hitler diaries.

446
00:33:42,521 --> 00:33:46,058
How does it feel
 to be homeless?

447
00:33:46,092 --> 00:33:48,694
I don't consider myself
 to be homeless.

448
00:33:48,727 --> 00:33:51,297
The entire world
 is my home,

449
00:33:51,330 --> 00:33:54,633
and my ceiling is
 god's beautiful sky!
 [ Chuckling ]

450
00:33:54,666 --> 00:33:59,071
- that's very poetic.
 - mm. One of yours?

451
00:33:59,105 --> 00:34:02,274
Yes.
 Don't give up 
 painting, kathy.

452
00:34:02,308 --> 00:34:04,810
You have a lot of talent,

453
00:34:04,843 --> 00:34:08,780
but you've got to learn
 to stop being so stingy
 with your paints.

454
00:34:08,814 --> 00:34:11,750
Paint is like food,
 a nourishment for the canvas.

455
00:34:11,783 --> 00:34:14,720
When a baby cries,
 the mother offers her breast.

456
00:34:14,753 --> 00:34:17,189
It's the same with painting.

457
00:34:17,223 --> 00:34:22,261
Listen to your canvas crying.
 Then feed it with the paints,
 and don't hold back!

